  "prompt": "Why in astronomy is distance measured in light \"years\"?",
  "response": "In astronomy, distance is measured in light-years because it provides a convenient way to express vast cosmic distances. A light-year is the distance light travels in one year, which is approximately 9.46 trillion kilometers (or about 5.88 trillion miles). Here are the key reasons for using light-years:\n\n1. Scale of the universe\n- Cosmic distances are incredibly large\n- Conventional units like kilometers become impractical\n- Light-years allow astronomers to express distances more concisely\n\n2. Speed of light as a constant\n- Light always travels at the same speed (299,792 kilometers per second)\n- This provides a consistent, universal measuring standard\n- The distance represents time light takes to travel\n\n3. Practical communication\n- Easier to say \"10 light-years away\" than \"94.6 trillion kilometers\"\n- Helps astronomers and scientists communicate complex distances quickly\n\n4. Relativity connection\n- Reflects Einstein's theory that nothing can travel faster than light\n- Represents a fundamental cosmic measurement\n\n5. Astronomical context\n- Matches the scale of interstellar and intergalactic spaces\n- Provides meaningful perspective on cosmic distances\n\nBy using light-years, astronomers can describe immense cosmic distances in a straightforward, comprehensible manner.",
